**Code Explanation:**

This script performs the ablation studies and uncertainty quantification as requested. First, it defines two new model architectures: `SingleBranchUNet` (for the no-CIB ablation) and `DualBranchUNetMCDropout` (for the no-spectral-loss ablation and the main model evaluation). Both architectures incorporate `nn.functional.dropout2d` layers with a custom `mc_dropout` flag to enable Monte Carlo dropout at inference time without affecting the standard evaluation mode. The `DualBranchUNetMCDropout` architecture is structurally identical to the original `DualBranchUNet` from Step 2, allowing the pre-trained weights of the main model to be loaded seamlessly. The script then trains the two ablation models (`no-CIB` and `no-spectral-loss`) using the exact same hyperparameters, random seeds, and composite loss function components as the main model. The `no-CIB` model is trained using only the SO-band inputs, while the `no-spectral-loss` model is trained with the spectral consistency loss weight (`lambda_2`) set to 0.0. Following the training phase, all three models (the two newly trained ablation models and the pre-trained main model) are evaluated on the held-out test set. The evaluation computes the Root Mean Square Error (RMSE), Structural Similarity Index (SSIM), and the mean cross-correlation coefficient (r_ell) across all multipole bins. These metrics are printed in a consolidated table to standard output for direct comparison. Finally, the script performs Monte Carlo dropout on the main model by running 20 forward passes on a single test batch with the `mc_dropout` flag enabled. This generates a pixel-wise uncertainty map (standard deviation across passes) alongside the mean prediction. A composite figure is generated and saved, visualizing the ground truth tSZ map, the MC dropout mean prediction, and the corresponding uncertainty map.

**Modifications:**

Added Monte Carlo dropout support to model architectures, implemented ablation training loops, added evaluation metrics for RMSE, SSIM, and cross-correlation, and implemented uncertainty map visualization.

